diff:1670574795:1667843376:=63,80c63%0a%3c #foxbegin 221209-083315-816810#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!The influence of spoken language on IPSL %0a%3c -> - haridesikan%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 00:33-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221209-083315-816810 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c While IPSL is its own language with grammatical structures distinct from those present in Hindi and English, there are some interesting elements borrowed. Specifically, puns are borrowed from Hindi; you may allude to a word by making a sign for another word that sounds similar in spoken Hindi. There are also minimal pairs for words that have very different meanings; the only difference between the sign for "cold" and "difficult" is a change in facial expression, indicating that these words may be considered to be tied closer together by some subset of the early speakers of IPSL than they are considered related by people speaking other languages.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://muse.jhu.edu/article/38403%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221209-083315-816810#%0a---%0a> %0a
