uage transcriptions should be made applicable to IPSL to bridge the gap between the hearing and speech impaired and the rest of society. %0a%3c %0a%3c The IPSL has been developed through contextual research and purpose suiting the Indian landscape, although some elements are derived from the British Sign Language.  For example, most IPSL signers nowadays use fingerspelling based on British Sign Language fingerspelling, with only isolated groups using an indigenous devanagari-based fingerspelling system. Despite the common assumption that Indo-Pakistani Sign Language is the manual representation of spoken English or Hindi, it is in fact unrelated to either language and has its own grammar.  It contains 33 hand poses including 10 digits, and 23 letters. Amongst the letters in IPSL, the letters ‘h’, ‘j’ are represented by gestures and the letter ‘v’ is similar to digit 2. One team working on real-time transcription of ISL is from the University of Mumbai, using techniques such as face detection, object stabilization, skin-color segmentation, followed by grid-based feature extraction and classification to identify in real-time ISL hand gestures.  %0a%3c %0a%3c Language transcription in itself is a challenging task for spoken languages with widely available datasets. It becomes exponentially more difficult to translate a region specific gestural language like ISL when the language itself is being developed at the same time, with around 300 interpreters for a language used by 15 million people. I want to highlight the technological aspect of this issue, as this forum reaches an audience that can help tackle such issues within their own communities as well from a variety of perspectives. Actionable change comes from collaboration among groups in varied spheres of life - be it legislation, art or technology - working towards a common goal.%0a%3c %0a%3c References:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indo-Pakistani_Sign_Language %0a%3c %0a%3c https://arxiv.org/ftp/a